          <!-- Unified Understanding -->
          <div
            class="bg-gradient-to-r from-slate-900/80 to-slate-800/80 rounded-xl p-6 md:p-8 border border-yellow-400/20 mb-8"
          >
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-yellow-400 mb-6 text-center">
              The Unified Truth
            </h3>
            <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
              <p class="text-white/90 leading-relaxed text-center mb-6">
                Whether understood as the <strong class="text-yellow-300"
                  >primordial light itself</strong
                >
                or as <strong class="text-yellow-300">Lord Brahma</strong> who embodies
                that light, both interpretations converge on one profound truth:
              </p>
              <div
                class="bg-yellow-900/20 rounded-lg p-6 border border-yellow-400/30"
              >
                <p
                  class="text-xl text-yellow-200 leading-relaxed text-center italic"
                >
                  "Hiraṇyagarbha represents the <strong
                    >first manifestation of consciousness</strong
                  > — the Ultimate Light that transcends physical illumination to
                  become the
                  <strong>Light of Supreme Knowledge</strong> (Jñāna Jyoti) itself."
                </p>
              </div>
              <p class="text-white/80 text-sm text-center mt-6 leading-relaxed">
                Just as gold is the most precious and radiant of worldly metals,
                Hiraṇyagarbha represents consciousness more brilliant, more
                precious, and more eternal than any material light — the very
                source from which all knowledge, wisdom, and existence emanates.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Vedic Context -->
          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6 mb-8">
            <div class="md:col-span-2">
              <blockquote
                class="border-l-4 border-yellow-400 pl-6 py-4 bg-slate-900/50 rounded-r-lg mb-6"
              >
                <p class="text-white/80 italic text-sm md:text-base mb-2">
                  "हिरण्यगर्भः समवर्तताग्रे भूतस्य जातः पतिरेक आसीत्।"
                </p>
                <p class="text-white/70 text-xs mt-2">
                  <strong>Rig Veda 10.121.1:</strong> "In the very beginning, Hiraṇyagarbha
                  came into being as the golden germ; born as the sole lord of all
                  that exists."
                </p>
              </blockquote>

              <div class="space-y-4 text-white/80 text-sm leading-relaxed">
                <p>
                  The <strong class="text-yellow-300"
                    >Hiraṇyagarbha Sūkta</strong
                  > (Rig Veda 10.121) is one of the most profound creation hymns,
                  describing the primordial consciousness that existed before time,
                  space, and causation.
                </p>
                <p>
                  This is the <strong class="text-yellow-300">self-born</strong>
                  (Svayambhū) reality — not created by anyone, but eternally self-existing
                  as the first syllable
                  <strong class="text-yellow-300">Om</strong> (Brahmākṣara), the
                  origin of all sound, all knowledge, and all creation.
                </p>

                <!-- Additional Context -->
                <div class="bg-slate-900/60 rounded-lg p-4 my-4">
                  <h5 class="text-base font-bold text-yellow-400 mb-3">
                    The Cosmic Waters & The Golden Embryo
                  </h5>
                  <p class="text-white/80 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3">
                    Before creation, there existed only the <strong
                      class="text-yellow-300">primordial waters</strong
                    >
                    (Ap, Salila) — the undifferentiated cosmic ocean representing
                    pure potentiality. Within these waters, Hiraṇyagarbha manifested
                    as the first point of consciousness, the <strong
                      class="text-yellow-300">bindu</strong
                    > from which the entire universe would unfold.
                  </p>
                  <p class="text-white/70 text-xs leading-relaxed">
                    This is why Brahma is called <strong class="text-yellow-300"
                      >Nārāyaṇa</strong
                    >
                    (नारायण) — "the one whose abode (ayana) is the waters (nāra)."
                    He floated upon the cosmic ocean as the golden seed of all existence,
                    containing within himself the blueprint of the entire cosmos
                    — the 14 lokas, the countless beings, and the laws of Dharma
                    that would govern creation.
                  </p>
                </div>

                <p>
                  The Sūkta describes how Hiraṇyagarbha possessed <strong
                    class="text-yellow-300"
                  >
                    absolute sovereignty</strong
                  > over all that would come to be. He was the
                  <strong>giver of life-force</strong> (prāṇa), the <strong
                    >establisher of firmament</strong
                  >, and the one who <strong>separated heaven and earth</strong
                  >. Through his divine will and creative power, he transformed
                  the unmanifest into manifest reality.
                </p>

                <div
                  class="bg-orange-900/20 rounded-lg p-3 border-l-4 border-orange-400 my-3"
                >
                  <p class="text-white/80 text-xs leading-relaxed">
                    <strong class="text-orange-300"
                      >Philosophical Significance:</strong
                    >
                    Hiraṇyagarbha represents the transition from <em>avyakta</em
                    > (unmanifest) to <em>vyakta</em> (manifest). He is the first
                    <em>kārya</em> (effect) arising from <em>kāraṇa</em> (cause),
                    yet paradoxically, he himself is <em>akārya</em>
                    (uncaused) — making him the bridge between absolute Brahman and
                    the manifested universe.
                  </p>
                </div>

                <p>
                  In Vedantic philosophy, Hiraṇyagarbha is also identified with
                  <strong class="text-yellow-300">Sūtrātmā</strong> (the Thread-Soul)
                  — the subtle consciousness that threads through and connects all
                  beings, like a string holding together beads in a necklace. This
                  universal connection establishes the fundamental <strong
                    >unity of all existence</strong
                  >, reminding us that all diversity emerges from the One.
                </p>

                <p class="text-white/70 text-xs italic">
                  Cross-cultural parallel: This concept echoes the Islamic
                  teaching "एक नूर से सब जग उपजा" (From one Divine Light, the
                  entire world emerged) — affirming the universal recognition of
                  the primordial luminous source.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

